<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-11-17T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-11-17T05:00:00-05:00" n="859" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d859">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/1902</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Norway</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SAG1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schmedeman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Christiania</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-11-17T11:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">November 17, 1915, 11 a. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 2.40 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>37. It has come to my knowledge that the British Government and the
                                Norwegian American Line nave made another agreement (see my despatch
                                No. 91<note n="1" xml:id="d859fn1">Not printed.</note>), from which
                                it would appear that the British Government waives the right of
                                search on condition that it be put in possession of the ship’s
                                manifests and that the line agree, upon being requested by the
                                British Minister at Christiania, to return to England such goods
                                destined for other countries as the British Government may
                                desire.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_SAG1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schmedeman</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>